The fix has been successfully applied and tested. Here's a summary of what was done:

## Problem Analysis
The issue was in the `FromStringDeserializer.java` class. When deserializing a string value that resulted in an exception, the code was directly throwing a `JsonMappingException` instead of using the `DeserializationProblemHandler` mechanism. This prevented the `handleWeirdStringValue` method from being called, which meant test handlers like `WeirdStringHandler` in the failing test case were never invoked.

## Solution
I changed the error handling in the `deserialize` method to use `ctxt.handleWeirdStringValue(_valueClass, text, msg)` instead of directly throwing an exception. This allows the deserialization problem handler to intercept the error and return an appropriate fallback value as specified by the handler.

## Changes Made
The patch replaces the exception throwing code:
```java
JsonMappingException e = ctxt.weirdStringException(text, _valueClass, msg);
if (cause != null) {
    e.initCause(cause);
}
throw e;
```

With a call to the problem handler:
```java
return (T) ctxt.handleWeirdStringValue(_valueClass, text, msg);
```

This change allows problem handlers to be properly invoked when string deserialization fails, which is what the test `ProblemHandlerTest::testWeirdStringHandling` expects. The test now passes successfully.

